===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|la|trans}} + {{m|la|vestite}}, form of {{m|la|vestiō||I clothe, I dress}} (as in English {{m|en|vestment}}, {{m|en|vest}}). Literally, a "cross-dresser". From {{m|en|transvestitism}}, from {{bor|en|de|Transvestitismus}}, coined in 1910 by {{w|Magnus Hirschfeld}} (the practice itself is much older).

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/tɹænzˈvɛstaɪt/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A person who sometimes wears [[clothes]] traditionally worn by and associated with the opposite [[sex]]; typically a male who cross-dresses occasionally by habit or personal choice.

====Usage notes====
* This term is relatively formal (Latinate); {{m|en|cross-dresser}} is more casual, but whereas the verb {{m|en|cross-dress}} is common, the verb {{m|en|transvest}} is quite rare.
* ''Transvestite'' should not be confused with {{m|en|transgender}} or {{m|en|transsexual}} (see those terms for more); transvestites are often happy with their gender and have no desire to change their sex, but simply enjoy being able to cross-dress from time to time. When speaking of to or about an individual who identifies as transgender, the term transvestite is typically seen as derogatory.
* The term should also not be confused with {{m|en|drag queen||person who performs femininity}} or {{m|en|drag king||person who performs masculinity}}; those terms are specifically for performers.

